          "body": "Verse 6 is the chapter's most concentrated pastoral moment. God prohibits fear three times in a single verse: 'neither fear them nor fear their words... neither fear their words nor be dismayed at their presence.' The repetition is not stylistic redundancy; it measures the magnitude of the temptation. The imagery deployed — thistles and thorns, scorpions — describes not only physical danger but the psychological sting of relentless opposition. Ancient scorpions were genuinely lethal; sitting among them is not a picturesque metaphor for mild social discomfort. God is acknowledging that the ministry He is calling Ezekiel into is genuinely dangerous. The reason for fearlessness is not that the danger is exaggerated but that the One who sends is greater than the danger. The same pattern governs Isaiah's coal to the lips (Isaiah 6:7), Jeremiah's 'do not be afraid of their faces' (Jeremiah 1:8), and the New Testament commissions of Matthew 10:28 and Acts 18:9-10. In every case God does not minimize the threat; He relocates the prophet's fear from the audience to the divine commissioner. The commission itself is the source of courage — not the prophet's personality, not the audience's receptivity, but the authority of the One who sends."
